  "texts": [
    "IntroductionGenerative language models (GLMs), such as GPT-4 (OpenAI, 2023) and Claude (Anthropic, 2024), have demonstrated powerful performance across a variety of language and reasoning tasks.",
    "In the field of education, researchers are exploring the extent to which these models can perform tasks such as automated essay scoring (Xiao et al., 2024), providing feedback to students (Carlson et al., 2023), individual tutoring (Chevalier et al., 2024), and more (Gimpel et al., 2023).Although GLMs show promise in automating certain educative tasks, there are critical limitations that hinder the possibility of wider implementation.",
    "For instance, Xie et al. (2023) have shown that GLMs can be \"jail-broken\" to bypass safety guardrails and can disclose personally identifiable information.",
    "Large GLMs are extremely large, requiring millions of dollars to train and deploy (Khowaja et al., 2024); as such, they are highly inefficient for specialized tasks, such as predicting political affiliation based on users' tweets (Yu et al., 2023).",
    "These models regularly undergo additional training; these updates raise issues around replicability, since models will generate different (and often less accurate) output, with the same input, even when temperature is set to 0 (Chen et al., 2023)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}